metadata.name: Sub Section Patina #644
metadata.description:
"Sub Section Patina" is inspired by street art and the marks and layering from that art form. If you zoom in on a small section of a wall that artists have marked, sprayed paint, and plastered with posters, some beautiful effects start to happen.

While the "Sub Section Patina" layers are building up, there is a tendency to destroy the layers below. The layering is similar to a wall many street artists have contributed. Sometimes just a section will be covered and filled with something else. Sometimes large areas of the canvas are covered up. Other layers will be put on top of one another, creating a new chaotic image. 

Features:
Four different sizes: 9x16, 11x14", 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one cyan, magenta, yellow and black, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
substack/point-in-polygon

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: Windowx #32
metadata.description:
"I know when you wake up
I already know your routine
Not that I'm on the lookout
But is that our time matches

If I catch you in the pool
massage my retina
I want you without a fissure
It is necessary to harden without losing tenderness

Early in the morning on the balcony
with a cup of coffee
The hair in disarray
So needy tsk, tsk, tsk

Coverage 04
message for you
In these empty days
There's nothing on TV
Coverage 04
Pretending not to see
my indiscreet window
right here in front

if you go to work
So my day ends
And then just start over
When your light shines

Your house has no walls
Not your bedroom
Your cover doesn't cover you
close your eyes tight
and try to sleep"

metadata.name: The Restoration Scheme: Shape Observation #61
metadata.description:
“Shape Observation” is the first episode of “The Restoration Scheme” Series. The work was based on Staghorn Coral. 

Living on the land, we have few opportunities to see corals in real life.
Most of my impressions of corals come from photos and illustrations.
So I think the first person who discovers coral must be stunned by its shape and color.
They may paint hundreds of pictures like this.

——

“The Restoration Scheme” Series

It’s a virtual action extended from the coral restoration plan led by Delta Electronics Foundation from Taiwan, consisting of five generative corals. Each of them was based on five different species of coral as the theme.

If collectors mint virtual corals, Delta Electronics Foundation will drop coral seedlings collectively in the sea. 

The project is powered by FAB DAO (Formosa Art Bank). The split will donate to the local organization from Taiwan dedicated to the coral restoration scheme.

——

About Delta 

Climate change is causing irreversible impacts. Coral reefs, known for their rich biodiversity and the capability to nourish a quarter of marine life, are at the forefront of the crisis. 

Also known as "tropical rainforests" in the sea, coral reefs have experienced five mass bleaching events in the past five years. Once global warming exceeds the 2˚C thresholds, it's likely that 99% of coral reefs will die off worldwide.

In addition to launching a coral restoration initiative along the northeast coast of Taiwan, Delta Electronics Foundation collaborates with Asia University to host "Earth Pulsing: Nurturing Life Exhibition" and releases the first art NFT featuring coral restoration. Through these actions, we hope to evoke public awareness of ecological issues. 

For more information, please visit https://delta50.deltaww.com/initiative/sea.html

——

Features
Iterations: 1 ~ 4
Tail: round, sharp
Feathering: yes, no
Color yes, no
Paper: normal, colored, white
Weight: regular, thin, bold
Special: -
Growth Speed: regular, slow, super slow

double click or press 's' to save as an image

made with p5.js

____________________________

《形狀觀察》為《恢復方案》系列第一作，品種為鹿角軸孔珊瑚。

在陸地上生活的我們其實能實際見到珊瑚的機會不多，我想起珊瑚的印象，最多是來自照片與畫。
於是想起了第一個發現珊瑚的人，一定會為他的形狀與顏色感到驚嘆不已。
所以我想像，他也許曾經畫下上百張類似這樣的畫面。

——

《恢復方案》
恢復方案是虛擬演算珊瑚實驗，一系列共五件的生成珊瑚作品，每一件對應到特定珊瑚物種。本實驗與台達電子文教基金會合作，藏家每收藏一件 NFT，台達電子文教基金會就會實際在海中植下一株對應的珊瑚苗。

這項專案與 FAB DAO （福爾摩沙藝術銀行）支援鑄造，部分分潤將直接捐助給台灣在地珊瑚保育組織，詳細資訊將於 FAB DAO Twitter 公佈。

——

關於台達電子文教基金會

氣候變遷引發許多不可逆的環境衝擊，以豐富生物多樣性著稱、滋養四分之一海洋生物的珊瑚，便是首當其衝的受害者。

被譽為「海中熱帶雨林」的珊瑚生態系，已在最近五年遭遇三次大白化，一旦升溫跨越攝氏2℃，屆時恐有多達99％的珊瑚瀕臨滅絕。

近年在東北角投入珊瑚復育的台達電子文教基金會，今年與亞洲大學共同策畫「地球˙脈動中」生態與藝術特展，並合作發行全台首見的珊瑚生成藝術NFT，喚起社會大眾對生態議題的重視。

更多資訊可參考: https://delta50.deltaww.com/initiative/sea.html

metadata.name: Pillars of Tomorrow #60
metadata.description:
Our vision is to create meaningful generative artworks that express human sentiments about their social experiences.

We’re currently focused on experiences centered around celebration, and we’ve chosen a theme that connects people through music.
Music has the power to evoke a wide range of emotions within us, especially when experienced through a collective experience.

We wanted to generate an artistic script that visually captures these expressions. 

Our first music NFT collection reflects human sentiments towards Tomorrowland 2022. 
It's a creative collaboration with dahleea, an artist dedicated to colors, who gave us the inspiration for the visuals you are seeing through one of her beautiful and colorful artworks.

Coding, music, and art collide to recreate emotions expressed by people coming together from all over the world to share music and connection at one of the world’s leading music festivals. 

The creative process:

Data was collected via emotion analysis using Twitter’s API. Our data is derived from emotion analysis models to extract the emotion scores (Happiness, Anger, Sadness, Fear, and Surprise) from 105,762 tweets, written in English, and containing mention of ‘Tomorrowland' between July 15, 2022, to August 8, 2022. 

Our analysis demonstrated the following emotions:

Happiness: 38%
Anger 8%
Sadness: 26%
Fear: 28%

Music:

In Pillars of Tomorrow, there are 4 instruments: bass, piano, percussion (hi-hat, kick, snare, claps, fx sounds), and a quiet pad. All the rhythms are self-written using Ableton, exported, and randomly selected to create the backbone of our generative music NFT.

This music piece has 4 different parts (basic, drop, break, after-drop) which are looped 3 times. All parts include different rhythm variations which are chosen randomly. 

The generative harmony is present in the basic and after-drop parts. The key to generating harmony is using the emotion percentages above as possibilities for the next piano chord and melody to sound happy or sad.  
We chose to distort our bass sound according to anger trait values, as distortion can turn a mild bass into an aggressive one. 

Finally, there is also an emotion of surprise, which is associated with a special background and the sound of bells ringing.  The surprise element trait of the mints will be revealed after the Pillars of Tomorrow collection is fully minted.

We wanted to make a dynamic collection that would give you the feeling of a live music event, an interactive experience. A big stage flowing with music and diverse human expressions.

p pause (or play)

space (play/stop)

l (change where the camera look)

Arrow Up (View pillars from above)
Arrow down (go to starting position)
Arrow left/right (camera moving direction)

AWSD work as arrows as well

For an optimal experience, we recommend using Google Chrome.

#CodingIsArt

metadata.name: Symbology437 #2
metadata.description:
Abstract, distorted compositions using symbols from the original IBM VGA codepage 437 character set. The symbols were created in code as bitmaps, scaled, and then drawn onto the canvas. The shading is based on the characters and sets from ANSI and ASCII art styles. 

There are 4 main types of outputs:
- Abstracts, 50%
- Random characters, 25%
- One of 16 preset character layouts, 25%
- One of 16 custom symbol PFP styles that will be 10% of the total outputs

For abstracts, there are several main styles created from layering different base shapes: circles, filled circles, rectangles, flow field lines, and rain-like streaks.

Color combinations include monochromatic, green or amber, dark mode, and multicolor.

Press 's' to save the image. The size is 2318x3000px, and for PFPs, the size is 3000x3000px.

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #203
metadata.description:
“Ordinary Places” is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher’s “Water Tower” photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha’s “26 Gasoline Stations” photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather’s farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Diffusion Walks: Series 1 #14
metadata.description:
Diffusion Walks: Series 1

first of all, zoom in. then zoom out. more.

implemented a modified "Image Random Circular Walker" 
to use sharp, rotating lines and jagged spirals instead of circular lines
by breaking radius/direction/angle a little bit, increasing stroke speed, 
and utilizing my own finetuned diffusion model outputs as inits for the new walking algorithm.


The new walk is some what of a frantic spidercrawl, accompanied by a shimmering dance.
I enjoy the glints of frenzy that this sort of motion adds to otherwise serene diffusion outputs.
Furthermore, there's something special about the output being revealed; re-distorting a guided
set of denoised images gives a lot of depth and momentum to the work for me personally.
It turns the process into a cycle.

fxrand() affects the init image, stroke speed, number of strokes, duration, stroke angle, and stroke sequence direction.

there are 25 image variations.
this is not about the images as much as it is about the walk.
there are countless walk variations.

duration, stroke angle and direction ranges vary as well.

there are 6 potential speeds.

as a result, hash variations will affect clarity, palette, init, and pattern of the token.

no recorded hash-unique features/attributes are printed on the token as a guide
please experience each variation's infinte iterations as their own realm
explore the variations, find different speeds and walker paths, enjoy the boundless variety in this set


zoom out to see the full image. zoom in for strokes. open live for easier zoom experience.
1280px by 1664px.

credits are important. when you play with a lot of things you made
mix them with things your friends made
and break things other people made
it is paramount to give all parties their flowers once
the art is made.

generated with my finetuned SD model, deforum notebook, and p5.js
credit to Vamoss for the original image walker algorithm (https://openprocessing.org/sketch/624879)
which was the basis for the new walker algo
credit to Stable-Diffusion team for original model which I tuned
credit to deforum team (which includes myself) for the deforum notebook

License included in License.md and p5.js file
License for Image Random Circular Walker and Diffusion Walks are both CC BY-SA 3.0

metadata.description:
“ostinato” by pixelwank 

“In music, an ostinato is a motif or phrase that persistently repeats in the same musical voice, frequently in the same pitch.”

Inspired by the musical term, the piece is constructed of many duplicate layers, creating a larger symphony.
